Introduction

We have been provided with the insurance data set to predict whether a customer will churn or not. I will perform an exploratory data analysis to dig deeper into the data set.The strategy will be, as the data set is said to be clean ,I will not waste much time in data wrangling part. I will investigate the data set for its each features and their individual distributions. After that i will try to perform a Bi-variate analysis and see how they are correlated with respect to other features and target variable. Then i will perform a feature selection process to select the most significant features in terms of their explainability of target variable. I will check the distribution of the target variable and if they are imbalanced , try different techniques to mitigate the imbalance problem in-order to get a reliable performance from the developed models. I will select two models and analyse the performance based on different performance parameters with some hyper parameter tuning. Finally, i will produce some marketing suggestion based on the knowledge i gained from the EDA and model performances.

  names=names(df_train)
   a=(names[x])
      plot1 <-  ggplot(data=df_train,aes_string(x=a),environment = environment())

plot2 <-
  plot1+
  geom_density(aes(fill = labels), alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "yellow"))

## This will generate the histogram of the feature for different target levels
plot3 <- plot1+geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..,color = labels,fill = labels),
                   position = "identity",alpha=0.2) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue"))

## This will arrange the two plots in one window
ggarrange(plot2,plot3,ncol = 1,nrow = 2)



}

Bi-variate analysis

We will load the data set again for Bi-variate analysis only, as correlation and other matrix only work with numerical data.

df_train_cor <- read.csv("trainSet.csv")

Some motivations

We have already performed the uni-variate analysis.Now we want to perform a Bi-variate analysis to see how our predictor variables are correlated with the target variables.We would like to select only those variables which can explain our target variable well or at least in a reasonable margin.On the other hand we need to identify any unnecessary variables which are highly correlated among them selves.The strategy would be if the variables have not enough explaining power for the target variable we would discard both the variables but if they have explaining power we would only keep the stronger one because the other will be redundant and reduce the performance of our predictive models.

In order to find out how the variables are correlated among each other, first we will generate a correlation matrix which can provide us with useful information. Later,for better visualization we would generate a corr-plot to figure out potential variables.Once identified we will only investigate the promising variables as our data set has 17 features and investigating all possible pair of features would be time consuming and unnecessary.

We also know that visualizing continuous variables in a scatter plots is more intuitive than continuous and discrete variables combination.So while performing the pair-plots we will only visualize the continuous pairs and keep track theoretically any other combination.

Correlation Matrix

cor(df_train_cor)

Motivation

Before developing any model we need to select two models as per the requirement of the assignment.Considering our data set, there are 16 features and 1 target variable.The target variable is categorical and some of the features too , so we cant use linear regression model.As we have 7 continuous variable and 8 categorical variables, we have choose a model which can work well with both categorical and numeric values.And as the target variable has only 2 separate levels i deiced to use
1. Binomial Logistic regression and
2. Random Forest

p_rf
## Error : The fig.showtext code chunk option must be TRUE
Comments:

We can observe from the comparison table that Model performance improved significantly accross the target level after the data has been balanced on both levels.The accuracy was very high before the data set was balanced.This is due to the fact the the target level which has higher frequency, played a major role in this accuracy.But target level with low frequency can suffer due to little learning during training phases.Thats why when we check sensitivity which determines how accurately it can predict churn rate , the model performed very poor. But when we balanced the dataset , the model got sufficient opportunity to learn from situations when the customer churns and performed way better.In this process we loose some capacity to identify the other level like when the customer will not churn but that is acceptable as by loosing a little we can improve a lot at our desired target level.

So we understand that we can improve the performance of the model based on the Business goal of the organization and in our case as the business goal was to predict customers with possibility to churn, i think my motivation to balance the data set is proved correct.

Selecting the final model

From the comparison graph from above two models under different combinations we can see that model generated by random forest algorithm performs better than the model generated with logistic regression.If we watch carefully among the two models, we can see that although Logistic regression done relatively well in case of predicting the Churn parameter but its performance reduced considerably in case of accuracy and specificity measures compared to random forest model.For a small gain(approx. 2%) in sensitivity the model is lacking significantly(appx. 8% in accuracy and appx.7.8% in specificity) in other measures.So i have decided to use random forest for my final algorithm in evaluating and predicting the target variable for this data set.

Model Interpretation and Inference

This is our final model that has generalized the test data quite well. I am happy with the performance , specially predicting the churn of the customer is at satisfactory level(appx.74% compared to the bench mark accuracy 12% for the imbalanced data set).The other measures are also satisfactory specially the accuracy which is (appx. 88%) close to our bench mark accuracy .In terms of model time complexity , with 5 fold cross validation model took 224.46 sec, compared to model without cross validation13.68 sec with the same level of accuracy.The time complexity increases exponentially with the cross validation tuned for parameters for higher values. I have run in one instance for number of folds=10, tunelength=10,.ntree=500 and waited for 40 minutes still the model was training and i had to shut down the process manually.

So we should consider this time factor in terms of model training and it should justify how much gain in performance we are getting at the expense of how much time we are investing and take our final decision in model selection.

Based on the above discussion we should go for a simple random forest model without cross validation as implementing cross validation does not add much value in gaining improvements in the performance compared to time and efforts it takes to achieve similar level of performance.

Marketing Suggestions

Below are some suggestions regarding Churn Rate in Marketing Perspective derived from the analysis:

  1. If our Business goal is identifying whether a customer will churn or not, we should give more focus on the accuracy on the level 1 of our target data set.

  2. For this, we can tune some parameters like cut off points to a higher thresh-hold value which will increase the predicting accuracy of churn rate.

  3. We have identified, feature_3 is the most important predictor in case of predicting the churn or No Churn of the customer.

This predictor alone can explain the target variable well with the accuracy of 73% and sensitivity of 63%. So, we should invest more time on the specifics of this variable for a customer and find ways to communicate and create several indicators in case something goes wrong about the customer based on this feature and give the highest priority in mitigating any obstacles the customer might have with respect to this feature.
